# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:167
msgid "## How to Run a Carpentries Workshop"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:169
msgid ""
"The [**Carpentries Handbook**](https://docs.carpentries.org/) is a community-developed resource that\n"
"provides tips, checklists, and points of contact for nearly all Carpentries-related activities in one location.\n"
"The Carpentries Handbook is the definitive source for policies and information.\n"
"Here, we will cover some information about actually running a workshop."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:174
msgid ""
"Briefly, there are two types of Carpentry workshops: centrally-organized and\n"
"self-organized. Centrally-organized workshops are organized by a team of\n"
"[Regional Coordinators](https://carpentries.org/regionalcoordinators/) who take care of logistics and administration such as\n"
"finding instructors and handling workshop registration. For self-organized\n"
"workshops, the organization hosting the event is responsible for these details."
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:180
msgid "> ## Workshops as an Instructor"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:181
msgid ""
">\n"
"> As an instructor, you may be primarily teaching at local workshops or you\n"
"> may not have local opportunities, or you may just want to\n"
"> teach somewhere else.\n"
">\n"
"> If you want to teach non-locally, you should be sure to join our instructor\n"
"> mailing list during the community exercise below, so that you hear about\n"
"> upcoming teaching opportunities.\n"
">\n"
"> Note that the Carpentries does not guarantee\n"
"> that instructors will get to teach at workshops after they are trained, so the\n"
"> best way to make sure that you get to teach (if you want) is to try running\n"
"> a workshop or even a single lesson yourself. It can seem daunting to organize\n"
"> your own workshop, but as long as you have 1-2 people who can either help or\n"
"> co-instruct, the Carpentries staff and community can provide\n"
"> support and guidance so that it's not so scary!"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:199
msgid ""
"In both cases (self- or centrally-organized), you can start the workshop\n"
"process by completing the [Carpentries workshop request form](https://amy.carpentries.org/forms/workshop/)."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:202
msgid ""
"For more details on how to run each type of workshop, see:\n"
"* [The Carpentries Handbook: Teaching and Hosting](https://docs.carpentries.org/topic_folders/hosts_instructors/index.html)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:205
msgid ""
"or the the following Lesson Program specific references:\n"
"* [Data Carpentry](http://www.datacarpentry.org/workshops-host/)\n"
"* [Library Carpentry](https://librarycarpentry.org/workshops/)\n"
"* [Software Carpentry](https://software-carpentry.org/workshops/request/) workshop pages."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:210
msgid ""
"Policies related to instructor training and workshops The Carpentries can be found in [the policies repository](https://github.com/carpentries/policies). Please\n"
"be sure to read through the [instructor no-show policy](https://github.com/carpentries/policies/blob/master/instructor-no-show-policy.md) before signing up for your first workshop."
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:213
msgid "### Setting Up"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:215
msgid ""
"In order to communicate with learners,\n"
"and to help us keep track of who's taught what and where,\n"
"each workshop's instructors create a one-page website with information about their workshop.\n"
"Once that has been created,\n"
"the host or lead instructor sends its URL to\n"
"the [workshop coordinator](mailto:team@carpentries.org),\n"
"who adds it to our records.\n"
"The workshop will show up on our websites shortly thereafter."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:224
msgid ""
"You may also create an etherpad for your own Carpentries-related events. When you point a browser to a url at\n"
"`pad.carpentries.org/name-of-pad` you will either arrive at an existing etherpad by that name or a brand new\n"
"etherpad with basic Carpentries information at the top.  For workshops we use `year-month-day-venue` as the name\n"
"to ensure unique names."
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:229
msgid "> ## Practice With The Carpentries Infrastructure"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:230
msgid ""
">\n"
"> Go to the [workshop template repository]({{ site.workshop_repo }})\n"
"> and follow the directions to create a workshop website using your local location and today's date.\n"
"> Put the link for your workshop website into the Etherpad.\n"
">\n"
"> This exercise should take about 25 minutes.\n"
">\n"
"> Note: Sometimes web browsers will cache the workshop webpage, so when\n"
"> you make changes in GitHub, they don't show up on the workshop webpage\n"
"> immediately.  Two ways to avoid this are to use a \"private\" or\n"
"> \"incognito\" mode in your web browser or by following these\n"
"> [instructions to bypass your browser cache](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Bypass_your_cache)."
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:244
msgid "> ## Question and Answer"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:245
msgid ""
">\n"
"> What questions do you have about running and teaching at a workshop? Talk with a partner and\n"
"> enter your questions into the Etherpad. At this time we will also return to discuss questions remaining from the beginning of the day.\n"
">\n"
"> Leave about 10 minutes for this discussion."
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:253
msgid "## A Culture of Contribution"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:255
msgid ""
"In the same way that we hope to promote a\n"
"culture of openness, sharing,\n"
"and reproducibility in science and research through training researchers with\n"
"the tools they need, the\n"
"Carpentry organizations themselves aim to be open, collaborative, and\n"
"based on best practices.  We want to draw together the collective expertise of\n"
"our teaching community to create collaborative lessons, share other materials,\n"
"and improve the lessons via \"bug fixes\" as we go along."
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:264
msgid "> ## Lesson Incubation"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:265
msgid ""
">\n"
"> Maybe this instructor training has inspired you to go home and write your\n"
"> own fantastic lesson!  If you'd like to model it after the Software and\n"
"> Data Carpentry lesson format, you can find a template and instructions in [the Carpentries lesson example repository]({{ site.example_repo }})."
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:271
msgid "> ## Many Ways to Contribute"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:272
msgid ""
">\n"
"> We recognize that the medium of GitHub may be restrictive to those\n"
"> who wish to contribute to our lessons.  We are always searching for\n"
"> ways to make the process more friendly to all, whether that be\n"
"> contribution training, or alternative routes to contribution.  If you\n"
"> have any ideas how we might make contribution more contributor-friendly,\n"
"> please let us know."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:281
msgid ""
"Being part of a friendly, open discussion, is of equal or greater importance\n"
"to the community than submitting the perfect lesson change.  The\n"
"[checkout process]({{ page.root }}/checkout/) to become a certified instructor will be\n"
"one way to start connecting to the community and find which area will allow you\n"
"to contribute best."
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:287
msgid "## The Carpentries Community"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/21-carpentries.md:289
msgid ""
"As you can imagine, based on the above, there are many aspects of running the Carpentries!\n"
"While there are a small number of dedicated staff who work for the Carpentries organization,\n"
"the real power of the Carpentries is in its community of volunteers that take on all sorts of\n"
"roles to teach and organize workshops, help produce and maintain lessons, and most importantly,\n"
"build local and global communities of practice around  skills for data analysis, computational thinking, and research software development. Our community depends on individuals like you who are passionate about expanding these communities of practice through inclusive and evidence-based instructional practices, and can contribute your perspective and expertise to continually refine our instructional materials and practices.  A full description of the breadth and diversity of community member roles, an overview of the Carpentries' various social media channels, a calendar of future community events, and descriptions of mailing lists used by the community can be found [here on the Carpentries website](http://static.carpentries.org/community/) and also on the [getting connected page](https://carpentries.org/connect/)."
msgstr ""

